<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-the-mean-value-theorem"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Mean Value Theorem</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The derivative is defined pointwise, but the next results show that it
      controls the global behavior of a function on an interval. Rolle's
      theorem and the Mean Value Theorem connect endpoint information with the
      derivative at some interior point. They are among the central tools of
      differential calculus.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-critical-points-and-rolle">
    <title>Critical Points and Rolle's Theorem</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-critical-point-theorem">
      <title>Critical Point Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon (a,b) \to \R</m>, and let <m>c \in (a,b)</m>. If
          <m>f</m> has a local maximum or a local minimum at <m>c</m> and
          <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>, then
          <md>f'(c)=0.</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>f</m> has a local maximum at <m>c</m>. Then for all
          <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>c</m>, we have
          <m>f(x)-f(c) \le 0</m>. If <m>x \lt c</m>, then <m>x-c \lt 0</m>, so
          <md>\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \ge 0.</md>
          If <m>x \gt c</m>, then <m>x-c \gt 0</m>, so
          <md>\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \le 0.</md>
          Since the derivative exists, both one-sided limits of the difference
          quotient equal <m>f'(c)</m>. Hence <m>f'(c) \ge 0</m> and
          <m>f'(c) \le 0</m>, so <m>f'(c)=0</m>. The proof for a local minimum
          is analogous.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-rolle">
      <title>Rolle's Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m>. Assume that
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>f</m> is differentiable on <m>(a,b)</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>f(a)=f(b)</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Then there exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that
          <md>f'(c)=0.</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem"/>, <m>f</m> attains an
          absolute minimum and an absolute maximum on <m>[a,b]</m>. If these
          are equal, then <m>f</m> is constant, so <m>f'(x)=0</m> for every
          <m>x \in (a,b)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Otherwise at least one of the two extreme values is different from
          <m>f(a)=f(b)</m>. If the minimum is different from <m>f(a)</m>, then
          the point where the minimum is attained cannot be <m>a</m> or
          <m>b</m>, so it lies in <m>(a,b)</m>. The
          <xref ref="prop-critical-point-theorem"/> then gives a point
          <m>c \in (a,b)</m> with <m>f'(c)=0</m>. The same argument works if
          the maximum is different from <m>f(a)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-mean-value-theorems">
    <title>The Mean Value Theorems</title>

    <p>
      Rolle's theorem is already useful, but its most important role is as the
      model for the Mean Value Theorem. The idea is simple: subtract a suitable
      linear function so that the new function has equal endpoint values, then
      apply Rolle's theorem.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-mean-value-theorem">
      <title>Mean Value Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m>. Assume that <m>f</m> is continuous
          on <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable on <m>(a,b)</m>. Then there
          exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that
          <md>f'(c)=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>s(x)=f(a)+\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}(x-a),</md>
          the secant line through the points <m>(a,f(a))</m> and
          <m>(b,f(b))</m>. Define <m>h(x)=f(x)-s(x)</m>. Then <m>h</m> is
          continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable on <m>(a,b)</m>. Also
          <md>h(a)=0=h(b).</md>
          By <xref ref="thm-rolle"/>, there exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such
          that <m>h'(c)=0</m>. Since
          <md>h'(x)=f'(x)-\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a},</md>
          we obtain
          <md>f'(c)=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.</md>
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-mvt-secant-tangent">
          <caption>For a differentiable function, some tangent line is parallel to the secant line joining the endpoints.</caption>
          <image width="52%">
            <shortdescription>A parabola on an interval with a secant line through the endpoints and a tangent line at an interior point having the same slope.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=8cm,
  height=5.8cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-0.2, xmax=2.4,
  ymin=-0.4, ymax=4.6,
  xtick={0,1,2},
  ytick={0,1,4},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$},
  clip=false
]
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:2, samples=100] {x^2};
  \addplot[red, thick, domain=0:2] {2*x};
  \addplot[green!60!black, thick, domain=0.2:1.8] {2*x-1};
  \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, blue] coordinates {(0,0) (1,1) (2,4)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-mvt-hypotheses-necessary">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Each hypothesis in the Mean Value Theorem is necessary.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The function
            <md>f(x)=\begin{cases}
            x &amp; \text{if } 0 \lt x \lt 1,\\
            0 &amp; \text{if } x=0 \text{ or } x=1
            \end{cases}</md>
            is differentiable on <m>(0,1)</m> and satisfies
            <m>f(0)=f(1)=0</m>, but it is not continuous on <m>[0,1]</m> and
            there is no <m>c \in (0,1)</m> with <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The function <m>f(x)=|x|-1</m> is continuous on <m>[-1,1]</m> and
            satisfies <m>f(-1)=f(1)=0</m>, but it is not differentiable at
            <m>0</m> and there is no <m>c \in (-1,1)</m> with
            <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-cauchy-mean-value-theorem">
      <title>Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f,g \colon [a,b] \to \R</m>. Assume that <m>f</m> and
          <m>g</m> are continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable on
          <m>(a,b)</m>. Then there exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that
          <md>f'(c)(g(b)-g(a))=g'(c)(f(b)-f(a)).</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Define
          <md>h(x)=(f(x)-f(a))(g(b)-g(a))-(g(x)-g(a))(f(b)-f(a)).</md>
          Then <m>h</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable on
          <m>(a,b)</m>. Also <m>h(a)=0=h(b)</m>. By
          <xref ref="thm-rolle"/>, there exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that
          <m>h'(c)=0</m>. Since
          <md>h'(x)=f'(x)(g(b)-g(a))-g'(x)(f(b)-f(a)),</md>
          we obtain
          <md>f'(c)(g(b)-g(a))=g'(c)(f(b)-f(a)).</md>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      Taking <m>g(x)=x</m> in Cauchy's theorem recovers the ordinary Mean
      Value Theorem. So Cauchy's version is a genuine generalization rather
      than a separate result.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
